## 5. Mouse Models of Neurodegeneration

### 5.1 Alzheimer's Disease Models

#### APP/PS1 (APPswe/PSEN1dE9)
- **Transgenes**: Human APP with Swedish mutation + PSEN1 with exon 9 deletion
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 3-4 months: First amyloid deposits in cortex and hippocampus
  - 6 months: Cognitive deficits (spatial memory); gliosis
  - 8 months: Dense, mature senile plaques
  - 12+ months: Extensive plaque burden, synaptic loss
- **No tau pathology** (only express APP/PS1, not human tau)
- **No significant neuronal loss**
- **Key antibodies**: 6E10, 4G8 (Abeta), Iba1 (microglia), GFAP (astrocytes)

#### 5xFAD
- **Transgenes**: Human APP with 3 FAD mutations (Swedish, Florida, London) +
  PSEN1 with 2 mutations (M146L, L286V)
- **Fastest onset and most aggressive amyloid model**
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 1.5 months: Intraneuronal Abeta42 accumulation
  - 2 months: Extracellular plaques in subiculum and cortical layer V; gliosis begins
  - 4 months: Plaques throughout rostral-caudal axis; initially compact/circular
  - 6 months: Significant synaptic loss, cognitive deficits
  - 9 months: Neuronal loss in layer V cortex and subiculum
  - 12-18 months: Irregular plaques with diffuse halo; extensive pathology
- **Does show some neuronal loss** (unlike most amyloid models)
- **No tau tangles** (but phospho-tau positive dystrophic neurites around plaques)
- **Key antibodies**: 82E1, MOAB-2 (Abeta42-specific), ThioS (fibrillar)

#### 3xTg-AD
- **Transgenes**: APPswe + PSEN1(M146V) + MAPT(P301L)
- **Only model with both plaques AND tangles**
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 3 months: Intraneuronal Abeta; early cognitive deficits
  - 6 months: Extracellular Abeta plaques
  - 7 months: Enhanced neuroinflammatory response
  - 12 months: Tau pathology (hyperphosphorylated tau, tangles)
  - 18+ months: Extensive plaques and tangles
- **Amyloid pathology precedes tau** (consistent with amyloid cascade hypothesis)
- **Key antibodies**: AT8 (phospho-tau), HT7 (human tau), 6E10 (Abeta)

### 5.2 Tauopathy Models

#### rTg4510
- **Transgene**: Human MAPT with P301L mutation under CaMKIIalpha promoter
  (regulatable with doxycycline)
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 2-3 months: Early tau hyperphosphorylation
  - 3 months: Cognitive deficits (spatial memory)
  - 4-5 months: Robust NFT-like pathology; neuronal loss begins
  - 5.5 months: Gross brain atrophy (forebrain shrinkage)
  - 8-10 months: Severe neurodegeneration, >60% neuronal loss in forebrain
- **Regulatable**: Doxycycline suppresses transgene → allows study of tangle
  effects after stopping tau expression
- **Co-pathology**: Phospho-alpha-synuclein and phospho-TDP-43 accumulate
  alongside tau, increasing with age
- **Key antibodies**: AT8, PHF-1, MC1, CP13 (phospho-tau epitopes)
- **Caveat**: Insertional disruption of genes at transgene locus (chromosome 12)
  may contribute to phenotype independently of tau

#### PS19 (P301S)
- **Transgene**: Human MAPT with P301S mutation under PrP promoter
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 3-6 months: Tau hyperphosphorylation, initial inclusions
  - 6 months: Tau inclusions in hippocampus, amygdala, piriform/entorhinal cortex
  - 9 months: Neuronal loss, gliosis, brain atrophy
  - 12 months: Severe pathology with motor deficits
- **Motor phenotype**: Hind limb paralysis and dystonia develop (PrP promoter
  drives expression in spinal cord)
- **Less aggressive than rTg4510** but more representative of human tauopathy
  distribution
- **Key antibodies**: AT8, AT180, AT100 (phospho-tau stages)

### 5.3 Synucleinopathy Models

#### Alpha-synuclein PFF Injection Model
- **Method**: Stereotactic injection of recombinant alpha-synuclein preformed
  fibrils into striatum (or other brain region) of wild-type or transgenic mice
- **Pathology timeline (wild-type mice)**:
  - 1-2 months: pSer129 alpha-synuclein inclusions at injection site
  - 3 months: Spread to connected regions (cortex, amygdala, SN)
  - 6 months: Dopaminergic neuronal loss (~30-35% in SNpc)
  - 6-12 months: Progressive motor deficits
- **Pathology timeline (A53T transgenic + PFF)**:
  - Much faster and more severe
  - 60 days: Bilateral pSer129 pathology in SN, spread to striatum/cortex/midbrain
  - 2 months: ~40% dopaminergic neuron loss in SNpc, motor deficits
  - BBB breakdown accompanies pathology
- **Key antibodies**: pSer129 alpha-synuclein, TH (tyrosine hydroxylase for
  dopaminergic neurons), DAT (dopamine transporter)

#### A53T Transgenic (Line M83)
- **Transgene**: Human SNCA with A53T mutation under PrP promoter
- **Pathology**: Homozygotes develop motor impairment and alpha-synuclein
  inclusions starting ~8-12 months; hemizygotes >20 months
- **Brainstem and spinal cord predominant** (PrP promoter pattern)
- **Accelerated with PFF injection** (see above)

### 5.4 ALS/FTD Models

#### SOD1-G93A (high copy)
- **Transgene**: Human SOD1 with G93A mutation (high copy number)
- **Most widely used ALS model** (since 1994)
- **Pathology timeline**:
  - 47 days: Neuromuscular junction degeneration (fast-fatiguable MNs first)
  - 8 weeks: Weakened muscle strength, motor incoordination
  - 12 weeks: Mild behavioral phenotype; subclinical pathology
  - 15 weeks: Synaptic activity damage; mitochondrial vacuolization,
    neurofilament inclusions, cytoplasmic SOD1 aggregates
  - 20+ weeks: Progressive paralysis → humane endpoint
  - End stage: ~50% motor neuron loss in cervical/lumbar spinal cord
- **TDP-43 pathology**: Cytoplasmic TDP-43 redistribution only at advanced
  disease stages (biochemically incomplete compared to human ALS)
- **Key antibodies**: ChAT (motor neurons), GFAP, Iba1 (gliosis), SOD1,
  pTDP-43 (late)

#### TDP-43 Models (multiple lines)
- **Key challenge**: TDP-43 overexpression is toxic even for wild-type protein
  (dose-dependent toxicity, not mutation-dependent)
- **Conditional models**: CaMKII-tTA x TDP-43 (regulatable) — develop dose-
  dependent motor neuron degeneration
- **PrP-TDP-43(A315T)**: Develop ubiquitinated TDP-43 inclusions, gliosis,
  motor deficits, but many pathological features differ from human disease
- **Key antibodies**: phospho-TDP-43 (pSer409/410), total TDP-43, ubiquitin

### 5.5 Mouse vs Human Pathology Differences

**Critical limitations to communicate to users**:

| Feature | Mouse models | Human disease |
|---------|-------------|---------------|
| Neuronal loss | Minimal in most amyloid models; variable in tau models | Severe, progressive |
| Tangle formation | Absent in amyloid-only models; present in tau/3xTg models | Core pathology |
| Brain atrophy | Only in aggressive tau models (rTg4510) | Prominent |
| NFT maturity | Less mature, fewer ghost tangles | Full maturation spectrum |
| Plaque morphology | Dense-core predominant | Mixed dense-core + diffuse |
| Co-pathology | Usually only the transgene product | Multiple proteinopathies |
| Time course | Weeks to months | Decades |
| Genetic basis | Familial mutations overexpressed | >95% sporadic |
| Glia response | Less complex | More diverse activation states |
| Neuroinflammation | Present but differs in detail | More complex, TREM2 variants |

### 5.6 Key Antibodies: Mouse vs Human Tissue

**Antibodies that work in both**:
- Iba1 (Wako 019-19741): Mouse, rat, human microglia
- GFAP (Dako Z0334): Mouse and human astrocytes
- AT8 (Thermo MN1020): Phospho-tau, works in mouse and human
- 6E10 (BioLegend 803001): Human Abeta (requires human APP transgene in mice)
- NeuN (Millipore MAB377): Mouse and human neurons
- Synaptophysin (Millipore MAB5258): Mouse and human
- PSD-95: Most antibodies work across species

**Human-specific antibodies** (will NOT work in wild-type mice):
- 6E10, 4G8: Recognize human Abeta sequence; only work in mice with human APP
- HT7: Human tau specific
- Most alpha-synuclein antibodies recognize both mouse and human sequence,
  but pSer129 antibodies vary in cross-reactivity

**Mouse-specific considerations**:
- Endogenous mouse amyloid does not form plaques (mouse Abeta42 sequence
  differs at 3 residues and is less aggregation-prone)
- Mouse tau has only 4R isoforms (humans have 3R + 4R)
- Must use antibodies targeting the transgene product (human protein) in
  transgenic models

