## 7. Emerging Techniques

### 7.1 Spatial Transcriptomics

**What it adds to histology**: Spatial transcriptomics maps gene expression
while preserving tissue architecture, linking molecular profiles to
histopathological features.

**Key platforms**:
| Platform | Type | Resolution | Genes | Strengths |
|----------|------|-----------|-------|-----------|
| Visium (10x Genomics) | Sequencing-based | ~55 um spots | Whole transcriptome | Unbiased, large area |
| Xenium (10x Genomics) | Imaging-based | Subcellular | ~500 genes (panel) | Single-cell, subcellular |
| MERFISH | Imaging-based | ~100 nm | ~500 genes | High spatial resolution |
| CosMx (NanoString) | Imaging-based | Subcellular | ~1000 genes | Single-cell |
| Stereo-seq | Sequencing-based | ~500 nm | Whole transcriptome | High resolution + unbiased |

**Integration with histology**:
- Same section or adjacent section can be stained for IHC after spatial
  transcriptomics
- AI foundation models (OmiCLIP, 2025) link H&E images to transcriptomic data
  (trained on 2.2 million paired tissue images across 32 organs)
- Multi-slice spatial transcriptomics can be registered into 3D volumes
  (VR-Omics tool)

**Application to neurodegeneration**:
- Map cell-type-specific gene expression changes around plaques/tangles
- Identify disease-associated microglial and astrocyte transcriptional states
  in spatial context
- Discover new cell-cell interaction patterns in disease
- Post-mortem human brain applications growing rapidly (2025 review in Brain)

### 7.2 Tissue Clearing and Light-Sheet Microscopy

**Purpose**: Make tissue transparent → image entire brain/organ in 3D with
light-sheet microscopy → comprehensive spatial analysis without sectioning.

**Key clearing methods**:
| Method | Category | Tissue type | Time | Compatibility |
|--------|----------|------------|------|--------------|
| iDISCO+ | Solvent-based | Whole mouse brain | 1-2 weeks | IHC compatible |
| CLARITY | Hydrogel-based | Thick slices/organs | Days-weeks | IHC compatible |
| CUBIC | Aqueous-based | Whole mouse brain | 1-2 weeks | Fluorescent protein compatible |
| uDISCO | Solvent-based | Whole body | 1 week | FP partially compatible |
| SHIELD | Crosslinking | Universal | Days | Highly multiplexable |

**What it reveals that sectioning misses**:
- Complete 3D distribution of plaques/tangles across entire brain
- Vascular network architecture in relation to pathology
- Long-range neuronal connections and their pathology
- True 3D cell counting without stereological estimation

**Limitations**:
- Antibody penetration depth limited even in cleared tissue
- Light-sheet resolution lower than confocal (especially axially)
- Generates massive datasets (TB per brain)
- Not yet routine — specialist equipment and expertise required

### 7.3 Cryo-EM of Aggregates

**What cryo-EM reveals that histology cannot**:
- Atomic-resolution structures of amyloid fibrils from patient brain tissue
- Different fibril polymorphs ("strains") that correlate with clinical subtypes
- Tau filament structures differ between AD, Pick's disease, CBD, PSP, CTE
- Alpha-synuclein fibril structures differ between PD, MSA, DLB
- TDP-43 fibril structures now being resolved

**Implications for histology**:
- Histological markers (AT8, pSer129, etc.) cannot distinguish fibril strains
- Same IHC pattern may represent different structural polymorphs
- Cryo-EM provides ground truth for what histology is detecting
- Understanding structural differences helps interpret why different diseases
  show distinct regional vulnerability patterns

### 7.4 Digital Pathology and AI

**Current state (2024-2025)**:
- Whole-slide imaging (WSI) digitizes entire histology slides at high resolution
- Deep learning models can detect and quantify:
  - Amyloid plaques (dense-core, diffuse, CAA)
  - Neurofibrillary tangles (pre-tangles, mature, ghost)
  - Lewy bodies
  - TDP-43 inclusions
  - Microglial activation states
  - Synapse density

**Key architectures**:
- **CNN-based**: U-Net for segmentation, ResNet/VGG for classification
- **Object detection**: YOLOv10 (2024) for plaque/tangle detection
- **Foundation models**: Trained on millions of pathology images, fine-tuned
  for specific tasks
- **Vision transformers**: Increasingly used for whole-slide analysis

**What this means for ImageJ users**:
- ImageJ/Fiji can run deep learning models via:
  - deepImageJ plugin (runs TensorFlow/PyTorch models)
  - StarDist (pre-trained for nuclear segmentation)
  - Cellpose (pre-trained for cell segmentation)
  - CLIJ2 for GPU-accelerated preprocessing
- For custom models: Train in Python (PyTorch/TensorFlow) → export →
  run inference in Fiji via deepImageJ or scripting
- QuPath (free, open-source) is increasingly preferred for whole-slide
  digital pathology AI analysis, with Fiji integration possible

**Advantages over manual counting**:
- Reproducible (no inter-observer variability)
- Faster (analyze entire slide in minutes)
- Quantitative (continuous measures, not ordinal scores)
- Can detect subtle patterns humans miss

**Limitations**:
- Requires training data (annotated by expert neuropathologists)
- May not generalize across staining protocols/scanners
- "Black box" concerns — interpretability is an active research area
- Regulatory considerations for clinical use

### 7.5 Multiplexed Tissue Imaging

**Technologies enabling high-plex spatial protein detection**:

| Technology | Markers per section | Resolution | Method |
|-----------|-------------------|-----------|--------|
| PhenoCycler (CODEX) | 40+ | ~200 nm | Iterative fluorescent oligo hybridization |
| MIBI-TOF | 40+ | ~260 nm | Metal-tagged antibodies + ion beam mass spec |
| IMC (Imaging Mass Cytometry) | 40+ | ~1 um | Metal-tagged antibodies + laser ablation |
| CyCIF | 20-60 | ~300 nm | Iterative IF with bleaching cycles |
| mIF (Opal/Vectra) | 6-8 | ~200 nm | Tyramide signal amplification |

**MIBI-TOF for neurodegeneration**:
- Demonstrated on archival human hippocampus tissue
- Overcomes autofluorescence problem (mass-spec based, not fluorescence)
- Brain tissue is notoriously autofluorescent → MIBI is advantageous

**PhenoCycler (CODEX)**:
- Up to 40+ antibodies on a single tissue section
- Uses oligo-conjugated antibodies with iterative hybridization/imaging/stripping
- Enables comprehensive spatial profiling of immune cells, neurons, glia,
  vasculature, and pathological aggregates simultaneously

**What this enables for neurodegeneration research**:
- Simultaneous detection of multiple proteinopathies + cell type markers +
  activation states on one section
- Single-cell spatial phenotyping of microglia (homeostatic vs DAM markers)
- Mapping cell-cell interactions (microglia around plaques, astrocyte-neuron
  contacts)
- Combined pathology-immune profiling in same tissue section

**Integration with ImageJ/Fiji**:
- Most multiplexed imaging data can be exported as multi-channel TIFF stacks
- ImageJ can handle visualization and basic analysis of multiplexed data
- QuPath better suited for whole-slide multiplexed analysis with cell
  segmentation and phenotyping
- napari (Python) increasingly used for high-dimensional image data

